div.p:
High-resolution TEM images of each sample with fast Fourier transform (FFT) analysis are shown in Fig.

 4c–e

. The pristine Si layer provided a large and clear Si crystallite phase with high crystallinity (Fig.

 4c

). However, as the amount of crystal growth inhibitor increased, the size of the Si crystals substantially decreased in the C(1.5)Si layer with the emergence of the SiC phase (Fig.

 4d

). Additionally, it is very difficult to distinguish the Si crystallite phase in the C(5)Si layer (Fig.

 4e

) because of its subnanometre size (inverse FFT images of SiC in Fig.

 4f,g

). These TEM results agreed well with the X-ray diffraction data and the calculation of the crystallite size. In this regard, we confirmed that the size of the Si crystals can be effectively tuned by the crystal growth inhibitor.

To further confirm the stability of subnano-sized Si, we investigated E-pSi-G, E-C(5)Si-G and ME-C(5)Si-C (Fig.

 5g

). As the Si content increased, E-pSi-G exhibited a poor cycle life with unstable cycling efficiency. However, E-C(5)Si-G still provided good cycling stability with gradually increasing cycling efficiency. We also compared ME-C(5)Si-C with commercial graphite to confirm the electrochemical stability of the C(5)Si layer by excluding the effects of the well-known stable nature of the graphite. Even though the specific capacity of ME-C(5)Si-C (1,262.3 mAh g

 −1

) is much higher than that of graphite (362.0 mAh g

 −1

), it shows comparable cycling stability (Supplementary Fig.

 25

shows detailed electrochemical tests including the half-cell and full-cell tests of ME-C(5)Si-C, ME-C(5)Si-C blending with graphite and graphite). This result indicates that the C(5)Si layer still demonstrates excellent cycling stability, even with approximately seven times more coating content than that of C(5)Si-G.
